o Luxembourg -- t13 Mobilities and Struggle: A Commentary -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCertain forms of mobility and multilingualism tend to be portrayed as problematic in the public sphere, while others are considered to be unremarkable. Divided into three thematic sections, this book explores the contestation of spaces and the notion of borders, examines the ways in which heritage and authenticity are linked or challenged, and interrogates the intersections between mobility and hierarchies and the ways that language can be linked to notions of belonging and aspirations for mobility. Based on fieldwork in Africa, Asia, Australasia and Europe, it explores how language functions as both site of struggle and as a means of overcoming struggle. This volume will be of particular interest to scholars taking ethnographic and critical sociolinguistic approaches to the study of language and belonging in the context of globalisation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aLanguage and culturevCase Studies. 0aMultilingualismxSocial aspectsvCase Studies. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aMultilingualism.  aSociolinguistics.  aidentity.  alanguage and globalization.  alinguistic anthropology.  alinguistic ethnography.  amigration.  apower.  aspace.1 aBaynham, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradley, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDailey-O'Cain, Jennifer, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDailey-O’Cain, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeumert, Ana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawkey, James, eco